    {
        "content": "<p>Sorry for the confusion. The more precise statement to translate should be: For any set A, there exists a set B containing A but not equal to A. So I was not talking about cardinality.<br>\nI feel like the right way is to make A type set alpha, and B type set beta, and assume there is an injection alpha -&gt; beta</p>",
        "id": 456779225,
        "sender_full_name": "Xiyu Zhai",
        "timestamp": 1722926081
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This idea cannot be formalised exactly as stated in lean because lean uses type theory as a foundation, not set theory. Lean only has subsets of a type, not abstract sets. The correct translation of your idea into type theory is: for any type A, there exists a type B and an injective but not surjective map from A to B. But in type theory it doesn't even make sense to ask if terms of two different types are equal so asking that A is a subset of B is not possible in type theory. This does not cause any problems in practice for doing mathematics in the systems.</p>",
        "id": 456780211,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1722926531
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks a lot!</p>",
        "id": 456780283,
        "sender_full_name": "Xiyu Zhai",
        "timestamp": 1722926570
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My motivation is that suppose that I have a perfect chatbot that helps me with autoformalization, what should it say when user presents such input?</p>",
